      "rationale": "Mesh sensitivity study performed on three grid levels (2.1M, 5.8M, 14.7M cells). GCI values for hemolysis index ranged from 8.2% to 22.4% across operating points, substantially exceeding the 5% acceptance threshold. The team noted that finer grids were computationally prohibitive but accepted the result without additional corrective action. Discretization error is not adequately controlled for the intended COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented and traceable to COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "In vitro hemolysis experiments conducted at 37°C with porcine blood at physiological hematocrit (40±2%). Flow rates and rotational speeds match the five COU operating points within ±2%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of predicted vs. measured hemolysis index with error metric reported.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. Mean absolute relative error of 18.3% reported. Systematic over-prediction at high flow rates noted but attributed to model form uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to COU decision criterion (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index RH, directly tied to the regulatory acceptance criterion. Secondary QoIs include shear stress distribution and exposure time histograms, which inform the hemolysis power-law model."
